moves.1. Nf3 f5: f5? This seemed like a mistake right away. I've seen this move vs d4 and also vs f4 Bird's opening. It comes up in the Kings Gambit, e4--e5, f4--f5, but here it isn't challenging anything and weakens the king-side.
moves.2. d3 e6 3. e4 fxe4 4. dxe4 Bc5 5. Nc3 d: It has led to this where White is clearly better as a result of Black's poor piece placement, backward e pawn, and lack of king safety.
moves.8. Na4 Bb6 9. Nxb6 axb6: Now Iv'e eliminated the strong bishop and the queenside now will not provide good castled protection.
moves.10. c4 c6 11. cxd5 cxd5 12. Bb5+ Nbc6: My bishops have a nice cross-fire attack going and all Black's minor pieces are tied up.
moves.13. O-O O-O 14. a4 Qe8 15. Be3 Qh5 16. B: Black didn't see the problem the rook lift at a3 was going to cause.
moves.22... Qf7 23. b4 Nf5 24. Bb6 Rf8 25. Bd3: Now is where I'm going to go to work--I have the space and the piece placement and what I want is to sacrifice the exchange at h6 and rip open his king position.
moves.29... e5 30. fxe5 Rxf1+ 31. Qxf1 Bxg4 32: He has to lose a piece in this sequence and again just didn't see it coming.
moves.34. h3 Qxe5 35. hxg4 hxg4 36. Qxg4+ Qg7: That definetly did it. Now it would be a matter of being careful not to give a stalemate.
moves.43... Kf6 44. Bd4+ Ke6 45. Kf3 h5 46. Kf: Black resigned here although it would have taken a little work to avoid a stalemate or a draw. But being a 1900 player, he felt this was his loss and took it like a man. Good game.
